ultimatescaler.options.worldgen.bigInteg: Rewriting the terrain generation using BigInteger, allows for more precise terrain offsetting in a wider range.
may cause the terrain generation to be much slower and consume more memory.
You need to restart the game to apply the changes.
ultimatescaler.options.worldgen.experime: Warning: Experimental features, unstable and may cause crashes or other issues.
ultimatescaler.options.worldgen.farlands: Note: Too large or too small values can cause problems with terrain generation, and the recommended range is 512~4294967295.
Custom the position of the Far lands by modifying the divisor in the MaintainPrecision method (default: 33554432).
Removed the Far lands, but the terrain stops generating at a extreme far distance (~1.05e+306).
ultimatescaler.options.worldgen.header: WARNING: Modifications may not be 100% in line with theoretical expectations.
ultimatescaler.options.worldgen.limitRet: Limit the return value of the maintainPrecision method
ultimatescaler.options.worldgen.maxNoise: Max return value of the method (10^n)
Setting to a specific value can remove the Fringe lands.
ultimatescaler.options.worldgen.simulate:
In vanilla Minecraft, due to integer overflow, the terrain of the End will be missing in several circular regions centered at the world origin (MC-159283), which are called "End Rings".
Since BigInteger does not overflow, End Rings will be removed, enabling this option will simulate the End Rings and allow them to be offset, but they may not match the original.
Without BigInteger rewrite, End Rings will always be generated and cannot be offset.
